          <div class="w-12/12 md:w-5/12 flex ">
            <div class="">
              <img width="800" height="800" src="https://peatlands.wetlands.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/2_800x800_3.jpg" class="object-cover fixed_image_ratio" alt="" loading="lazy" srcset="https://peatlands.wetlands.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/2_800x800_3.jpg 800w, https://peatlands.wetlands.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/2_800x800_3-300x300.jpg 300w, https://peatlands.wetlands.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/2_800x800_3-150x150.jpg 150w, https://peatlands.wetlands.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/2_800x800_3-768x768.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" />                          </div>
          </div>
          <div class="w-12/12 md:w-7/12 flex flex-col items-center justify-center py-8 ">
            <div class="two_card_content">
              <div class="two_card_title font-bold text-lg sm:text-xl md:text-2xl lg:text-3xl pb-2">Achievement: Scaling Up Restoration in Indonesia</div>
              <div class="two_card-content font-normal text-md sm:text-lg md:text-xl lg:text-2xl"><p>Restoring peatlands is nearly always starts by repairing the damage to hydrology done by drainage. In response to major peat fires in Indonesia, we piloted the partial rewetting of 60,000 hectares of drained and degraded peatlands in the Ex-Mega Rice Project area in Central Kalimantan (Borneo), using our practical experience to develop ditch-blocking manuals that guided community-level action.</p>
<p><a class="cta-button lightbox" href="https://peatlands.wetlands.org/achievement-scaling-up-restoration-in-indonesia/">Read more</a></p>
</div>
